node.text:
TW: ED and Suicide. 

As a man who grew up with a father who showed literally no emotions, this is what I struggle with most. Some people are even surprised a man started @asafeplaceinsideyourhead. The whole reason I started it was because I felt alone, I felt isolated and like I couldn’t ever talk about how I truly felt. I’ve been suicidal, I’ve been down in the dumps and I’ve been at some of my lowest points and I’ve been met with “just man up” or “don’t be such a pussy”. It wasn’t until my brother completed suicide, that I understood just how detrimental these statements were to me. I go through periods of vast depression and my own father just “can’t understand why I’m so sad”. He never received the love he deserved as a child and passed it down to me and my brothers…well the generational trauma stops now. It ends with me. In being authentic with my mental health I hope to inspire other men to do the same. You are not weak, you are not less of a human being, you will not be considered not worthy of love by being honest. Opening up can save your life and inspire other men to do the same. Please keep going, I know it’s hard but I’m right here with you. - @tanner_hamilton22

Employers that work you with no days off and long hours.

Friends that don’t honor a no when you say you don’t want to hang out. 

It’s ok to not be ok but only when it’s not inconvenient for others… those people. 

Hard stop 🛑 

Please continue to defend your right to have mental health balance. Please say no when it doesn’t feel right to be somewhere or do something that you don’t want to.  We end the stigma when we speak loud about how we feel. 

It really is ok to not be ok and when you’re not, to protect your peace ☮️

node.text:
I like this idea so much more than being told that toxic people are attracted to empaths. It literally puts the blame on me for attracting them.

Hard facts is the empath in me keeps them around.  Because the broken should help the broken, right? No… we shouldn’t, at the expense of healing ourselves. We can’t heal toxicity in others.  Try to recognize it and learn to walk away. 

Don’t let the good in you be taken for granted. And work on fixing yourself first before you try to fix others. You deserve the love 💗 you give to everyone else. - @therealjoirizarry
